<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-478-386  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 478 386.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 28 1990 v7 n21 p5(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MCI, EasyLink latest to forge X.400 E-mail network links.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Musich, Paula.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   MCI Communications Corp. (contracts)Western Union Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    MCIC; WU.andO;Product:   EasyLink (Electronic mail system) (contracts).andO;Topic:     Electronic mail systemsX.400 ProtocolMarketing Agreements.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MCI, EasyLink Latest To Forge X.400 E-Mail Network LinksandM;The universe of electronic-mail subscribers who can exchange messages willsoon be much bigger, thanks to agreements announced last week between MCICommunications Corp. and eight other E-mail providers.andM;MCI agreed to interconnect its MCI Mail service with Western Union Corp.'sEasyLink public messaging service, as well as with the E-mail networks ofGeneral Electric Information Services, Infonet, Dacom Korea, OTC Australia,Swiss PTT, Transpac France and Telecom Australia, according to MCI officials.andO;The systems will use the international X.400 messaging standard tointerconnect their respective E-mail networks, the officials added.andM;The agreements announced last week continue a trend that began earlier thisyear, according to Eric Arnum, editor of Electronic Mail and Microsystems, anE-mail newsletter based in New Canaan, Conn.andP;  &quot;We're a little more than halfdone in getting all of the major [U.S.] carriers interconnected,&quot; said Arnum.andM;MCI, based in Washington, has already struck X.400 interconnection agreementslinking MCI Mail with services including ATandamp;T Mail, Dialcom, SprintMail andIBM's Information Network.andP;  Western Union, of Upper Saddle River, N.J., hassimilar agreements with all of those carriers except Dialcom.andM;MCI, with 110,000 mailboxes, and Western Union, with 210,000 mailboxes, areamong the larger electronic-mail systems in the United States, according toArnum.andM;MCI will provide on-screen help to guide users through proper addressingprocedures to access another mail system.andP;  Customers must know the user nameor account number required by a particular service to send messages.andM;Although testing of X.400 links between the two providers has not yet begun,MCI officials expect the connection to be completed this summer.andP;  There willbe no extra charge to subscribers of either service for accessing the X.400links.andO;</TEXT></DOC>